:::summary
Edmund Burke (1729–1797) was the Irish-born British statesman and philosopher who is regarded as the father of modern conservatism — a thinker whose profound critique of the [French Revolution](article.html?id=french-revolution) in his *Reflections on the Revolution in France* (1790) articulated the enduring case for ordered liberty, inherited institutions, and the accumulated wisdom of tradition over abstract ideological radicalism.
:::

